"SECTION5_PARAGRAPH1" = "New conditions, such as anemia, can come up during pregnancy and while you’re lactating. Your care team can help you safely navigate which medications you should add to address new needs.";
"SECTION3_PARAGRAPH1" = "When discussing your medications with your doctor, bring up everything you’re taking including over-the-counter meds such as a sleep aid, painkiller, or cough medicine. You should also bring up any ongoing conditions you have. Your care team can help you understand which medications to take and still meet your needs.";
"SECTION6_LIST_ITEM2" = "What would be the risks and benefits of taking or stopping a medication?";
"SECTION5_PARAGRAPH3" = "After pregnancy, you may require new medications as well for pain management, mastitis (swelling in the breast or chest tissue), or postpartum depression and anxiety. It’s a good idea to bring up any new concerns or questions you have to your care team.";
"SECTION1_PARAGRAPH1" = "Nearly everyone takes a medication at some point. If you’re pregnant or lactating, it’s particularly important to pay attention to the medications you’re on. The majority are safe to use, but there are certain ones you may need to avoid before, during, or after a pregnancy. Discuss your full list of medications with your care team if you’re pregnant or looking to become pregnant sometime soon.";
"SECTION4_PARAGRAPH2" = "Some medications are better tolerated by pregnant people and the developing fetus. For instance, acetaminophen is often suggested to treat pain during pregnancy. Other pain relievers, such as ibuprofen, are not recommended due to fetal side effects, such as problems with kidney development.";
"SECTION6_LIST_ITEM4" = "Which medications, vitamins, supplements, or over-the-counter medications should I avoid?";
"SECTION5_HEADER" = "New Medications and Pregnancy";
"SECTION6_PARAGRAPH2" = "You can also track your medications and learn more about what you’re taking in Health.";
