"SECTION6_HEADER" = "Questions You May Want to Ask Your Care Team";
"SECTION6_PARAGRAPH1" = "Taking medications during pregnancy is common. Your care team can work with you to develop a plan that meets your needs and those of the developing fetus or infant. Caring for your health and wellbeing is important. Medications are a helpful tool in making sure you remain healthy before, during, and after pregnancy.";
"SECTION6_LIST_ITEM1" = "Are the medications you’re taking safe to use during pregnancy and lactation? Make sure to include supplements, vitamins, and over-the-counter medications.";
"SECTION5_PARAGRAPH2" = "Medications may be needed to treat certain vitamin deficiencies or reduce the risk of preeclampsia (high blood pressure during pregnancy). Other times, routine blood tests can identify pregnancy-specific conditions, such as gestational diabetes. These conditions can typically be managed with medication and changes to daily habits. Addressing these conditions quickly can also prevent preterm birth and other complications.";
"ARTICLE_DESCRIPTION" = "It’s important to understand benefits and risks of taking medications while you’re pregnant.";
"SECTION4_PARAGRAPH3" = "As your body changes, your care team may suggest adjusting your medications along the way. Certain medications are safe at one stage like your first trimester, but shouldn’t be taken at another stage.";
"SECTION4_PARAGRAPH1" = "While you’re pregnant, it’s important to treat ongoing conditions such as high blood pressure or diabetes. If untreated, they can pose a risk to you and the fetus. Do not stop taking your medications without talking to your care team first.";
"SECTION3_PARAGRAPH2" = "It can also be beneficial to have a conversation with your care team before you’re pregnant. Having a discussion early can help you prepare for and manage symptoms and conditions, including headaches or allergies. The World Health Organization (WHO) also recommends taking a prenatal vitamin or folic acid (vitamin B9). Taking folic acid at least one month before getting pregnant can help prevent birth defects of the brain and spine.";
"SECTION2_PARAGRAPH1" = "A medication is a substance that’s used to prevent or treat symptoms or conditions. There are two major groups: those that require a prescription from a doctor and those you can buy over-the-counter without a prescription. Vitamins, supplements, and minerals are all considered medications.";
